article.description: Chris Webber had 19 points and 12 rebounds, and Bobby Jackson ignited the Kings in the fourth quarter with 10 points as Sacramento pulled away for a 99-79 victory over the Atlanta Hawks on Tuesday night.
article.headline: Seven Kings in double figures
article.linkText: Kings get points everywhere in beating Hawks
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Bobby Jackson picked an appropriate time to supply his typical energy boost for the Sacramento Kings. Chris Webber had 19 points and 12 rebounds, and Jackson ignited the Kings in the fourth quarter with 10 points as Sacramento pulled away for a 99-79 victory over the Atlanta Hawks on Tuesday night. "We see that from Bobby every night. We're only surprised when it doesn't happen," said Vlade Divac, who had 14 points and 10 rebounds. Jackson scored 13 points, while Mike Bibby, Predrag Stojakovic and Doug Christie each had 12 points. Clinging to a three-point lead, Jackson made a 3-pointer to open the fourth, igniting a 10-0 run. Three straight Atlanta turnovers led to seven more points, with Jackson making another 3-pointer from the corner to put Sacramento ahead 79-66 at 9:45. "I try to do a lot of things off the bench, whatever it is we need," Jackson said. "I knew we needed some energy and I was able to help pick us up on offense and defense." Sacramento, which had its 20-game home winning streak snapped Sunday night by Seattle improved to 28-2 at home and their league-leading record to 40-13. Shareef Abdur-Rahim, who averaged 29.6 points in his previous seven games, was held to 12 points and nine rebounds for the Hawks, who had won three straight and five of six. He shot 6-of-18 and did not attempt a free throw as Webber and the Kings held the All-Star forward in check. "Shareef is a heck of a player, you have to be careful with him," said Webber, who talked with the media for the first time since a blowup a week ago. "You have to keep the ball out of his hands and make him work." Jason Terry led Atlanta with 17 points, and DerMarr Johnson scored 13. "We had some lapses where we just hurt ourselves in the fourth quarter," Abdur-Rahim said. "We were only down three on the road, but they had that 10-0 run and all of a sudden we're down by 13." It was a rare victory for the Kings over the Hawks, who had beaten Sacramento 10 straight times before losing last February at Arco Arena. Atlanta had won four of the last five meetings in Sacramento. Down by 11 at the half, the Hawks used some strong perimeter shooting to cut the Kings' lead. Johnson made two 3-pointers as Atlanta pulled to 69-66 entering the fourth. "The Hawks are a very good team," Divac said. "They won their last five of six. They didn't quit and they almost came back. After our loss the other night, no one wanted to lose two in a row." Divac scored nine of his 11 points in the first, helping the Kings take a 50-41 lead into the break. Sacramento did a nice job defensively on Abdur-Rahim, who missed 7-of-9 shots in the first half and scored four points. "I thought tonight was a case of a little too much Sacramento balance and too many guys that can score," Atlanta coach Lon Kruger said.

Game notes
The Kings opened by making nine of their first 11 shots, and led 30-22 after one quarter. ... Hawks backup point guard Jacque Vaughn has played in 171 straight games. ... Atlanta is 24-7 against the Kings since they relocated in Sacramento during the 1985-86 season. ... The Hawks are 7-22 on the road this year.
